    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Lockerbie, in Translation</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Brigitte Andreassier-Pearl letter warns that only properly trained translators are qualified to work on crucial testimony in trial of two Libyans in bombing of Pan Am plane over Lockerbie, Scotland (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>You report that lawyers for the two Libyan defendants in the Lockerbie trial ''were getting poor translations of witness testimony'' and that the court ordered ''an inquiry into the ability of the interpreters'' (news item, June 10). As a professional simultaneous interpreter at the United Nations, I can testify that all too often people who ''know'' foreign languages declare themselves to be interpreters. But you need specialized training to acquire the skill necessary for professional recognition as a simultaneous interpreter.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>You report that lawyers for the two Libyan defendants in the Lockerbie trial ''were getting poor translations of witness testimony'' and that the court ordered ''an inquiry into the ability of the interpreters'' (news item, June 10). As a professional simultaneous interpreter at the United Nations, I can testify that all too often people who ''know'' foreign languages declare themselves to be interpreters. But you need specialized training to acquire the skill necessary for professional recognition as a simultaneous interpreter.</p>
        <p>This trial is highly sensitive and is followed throughout the world. Interpretation of the proceedings should be assigned to the most qualified interpreters the profession can offer.</p>
        <p>BRIGITTE ANDREASSIER-PEARL  New York, June 13, 2000</p>
      </block>
